instruction:
Calls arriving at the exchange (with infinitely many channels) follow a Poisson process with an arrival rate of $\lambda$, and each call duration follows an exponential distribution with a mean of $1 / \mu$. Let $X(t)$ be the number of calls in progress at time $t$. What is the probability that there are no calls in the process?

Options:
A. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\mu^2} {\lambda} ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
B. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\mu} {\lambda} ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
C. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\lambda} {\mu} ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\mu t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
D. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\mu} {\lambda} ( 1+\mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
E. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\lambda \mu ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\mu t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
F. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\lambda+\mu} {\lambda} ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\mu t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
G. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\lambda} {\mu} ( 1+\mathrm{e}^{-\mu t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
H. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{1} {\mu} ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\lambda t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
I. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\lambda \cdot t ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\mu t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
J. $$
\begin{array} {c} {{{P \{X ( t )=0 \}=\operatorname{e x p} \Bigl[-\frac{\lambda^2} {\mu} ( 1-\mathrm{e}^{-\mu t} ) \Bigr]}}} \\ \end{array}
$$
